    "recap_headline": "Georgia Southern University",
    "recap_text": "North Augusta, S.C.. \u2014\nThe Georgia Southern baseball team (5-11, 0-0 SBC) took down the Clemson Tigers (15-2, 0-0 ACC) by a score of 6-1 on Tuesday night (March 10th) at SRP Park.\nHOW IT HAPPENED:\nTwo walks in the opening frame issued by the Tigers resulted in runners on the corners for the Eagles, but a popout would retire the side without any damage.\nA leadoff double in the second by\nMax Prozny\n, followed by two free bases issued to\nBrady Christman\nand\nGrant Jordan\n. With two away and the bases juiced,\nJames McCoy\ndrew a walk to give the Eagles the first run of the evening. A wild pitch on the ensuing batter doubled up Southern's runs in the inning.\nWith the bases still loaded,\nSean White\nwould clear them with one swing of the bat, a beam to right center field that traveled 385 feet, extending the lead to 6-0.\nA one-out home run by former App State Mountaineer Ty Lichtenberger would make it a five-run contest in the home second, but no other Tigers would reach on.\nIn the Clemson third,\nCarter DeGondea\nwould pick up his third K in as many innings as he sat down Savoie to end the frame.\nThe fourth started with a leadoff single by\nJack Myers\n, who advanced on the play into scoring position after the second error of the night by the Clemson third baseman. However, he would be stranded at third to keep the score still 6-1.\nAlex Mason\nentered for the Eagles in the fifth, allowing just a single in the inning, and finishing the frame with his first strikeout of the night.\nIn the Tigers' sixth, two routine outs on 2-2 pitches were preceded by a walk issued. However, Clemson ended their fourth straight scoreless frame with a fly ball caught by\nMason Gazaway\non the warning track.\nMax Prozny\ndelivered another leadoff double in the seventh, this time to the right-center gap. Unfortunately, he would be stranded at second after three quick outs.\nIn the Tigers' seventh, they threatened with two singles with one away.\nCraig Kalkbrenner\nwould enter and retire the next two batters to give the momentum back on the side of Southern.\nConsecutive two-out hit batters for the Eagles put two on in the eighth for Southern, but a strikeout from Trammell ended the frame.\nIn the ninth, Clemson once again put a runner on but Kalkbrenner slammed the door yet again. This time, it was a K to end the night with an Eagle win.\nNOTES:\nThe grand slam by\nSean White\nwas the first by an Eagle since\nSam Blancato\ndid at South Carolina on April 3rd, 2024.\nThe victory over the Tigers was the first over a top-12 team since number ten Texas State in 2022, and the first over Clemson since 2016.\nMax Prozny\nwould have a 3-4 night of his own, his first three-plus hit game of his career.\nAlex Mason\nand\nCraig Kalkbrenner\n, both sophomores, combined for five innings of scoreless ball on the mound. They only allowed four hits and struck out a combined three Tigers.\nUP NEXT:\nThe Eagles kick off Sun Belt play this weekend with a three-game stretch at James Madison. First pitch Friday afternoon in Harrisonburg is set for 4 PM."
